items.prompt: Avery was debating on taking up German instead of Latin, because the _ was old.
items.response:
But then she remembered how her father had once tried to teach her how to play the guitar, and how she had been too embarrassed to practice. It was too late to start now.

_There's no point in learning a dead language,_ she thought. _I'll never use it._

Avery walked back to her dorm and lay down on her bed, staring up at the ceiling.

What if she had been wrong about the _?_ What if she had taken Latin and now she was trapped in a dead language?

She couldn't do anything about it now. She had to be patient. She would just have to keep studying Latin and hope that one day she would be able to use it.

#

The next day, Avery started her first class.

"I'm Avery," she said to the professor, who was a short, balding man with a mustache. "I'm taking Latin."

"Welcome, Avery," the professor said. "You're going to have a great time. Latin is the language of the gods."

Avery smiled. She didn't think she was going to have a great time, but she was determined to make the most of it.

She started to study the Latin alphabet and quickly picked up the language. Her parents were proud of her, and so was the professor.

Avery was determined to prove to them that she was not a quitter. She was determined to become a successful, well-rounded student.

After her first week of Latin, Avery was astonished to find that she was actually enjoying it.

"I'm really enjoying this," she said to her parents one day. "I never thought I'd like Latin. But I really do."

"I'm so proud of you, Avery," her mother said.

Avery was proud of herself, too. She had worked hard and she had succeeded.

#

One day, Avery was sitting in the library, reading a book.

"I'm so glad I found you," a voice said.

Avery looked up. It was the same boy who had talked to her the day she arrived at the Academy.

"You know, I thought I'd never find you again," he said.

Avery smiled. "I'm glad you did. It's nice to have a friend."

"I'm glad I found you, too," the boy said.

Avery couldn't help but notice that he had been looking at her with a certain kind of longing.

"I've been thinking about you a lot," he said.

"Really?"

"Yes, and I'm sure I'm not the only one. I think you're special."

Avery blushed. "I don't know what to say."

"Say you'll go out with me."

Avery hesitated. "I don't know..."

"You don't have to say yes right away. Think about it."

Avery looked away. She had never been out on a date before. She was afraid she would make a fool of herself.

"Avery?"

Avery looked back at the boy. "I'm not sure," she said. "I'd like to think about it."

The boy smiled. "I understand. Just give me your number and I'll call you later."

Avery took out her notebook and wrote down her phone number. She felt a little better. She had a date.

#

The next day, Avery got a phone call.

"Hi, this is the boy from the library," the boy said. "I'm calling to set up a date with you. What do you say?"

Avery smiled. "Yes, that sounds great."

"I'll pick you up at seven o'clock. Do you know where the library is?"

Avery nodded. "I know the way."

"Great. See you then."

Avery had never been more excited. She couldn't wait to go on her first date.

#

Avery got ready for her date. She put on her favorite jeans and a black T-shirt. She wanted to look nice.

At seven o'clock, the boy arrived. He was wearing a suit and tie.

"Wow, you look great," Avery said.

"Thanks," the boy said. "I thought I'd be more comfortable in casual clothes, but it's a little cold for that."

"It's not that cold," Avery said.

The boy looked at her. "I hope you're not cold, too."

Avery smiled. "No, I'm fine."

They got into the car and drove off.

"So what do you say, Eliza? Want to try some of this amazing menudo?" Dennis asked.

I shrugged. "Sure, why not?"

Dennis and Chastity both laughed and I suddenly felt awkward.

"I'm really not much of a drinker," I said.

"It's not a problem," Chastity said. "We don't need you to drink it. We'll just order the food and you can sit and watch."

I nodded and watched as Dennis and Chastity ordered their food.

I looked at the menu and decided on the menudo. I was so hungry that I could barely wait for it to arrive.

The waitress brought the food and I took a bite. It was the most delicious thing I'd ever tasted.

"It's delicious," I said.

"It's not bad," Dennis said. "I can't believe you didn't try it before."

I shrugged. "I just never thought I'd be in a place like this."

"What do you mean?" Chastity asked.

"Well, you know, I always thought I'd be the kind of guy who'd stay in a small town and get a steady job and live a normal life."

"And you don't anymore?" Chastity asked.

"I don't know. I guess I just want more out of life."

"That's a good thing," Chastity said.

I nodded and smiled. I was still having a hard time believing that I'd been given the chance to live in a different world.

"So what do you think?" I asked.

"I think it's a great thing that you're doing," Chastity said.

"I think it's the best thing I've ever done," I said. "I just hope I can do it for a long time."

"You can do it," Chastity said. "You've already made a big change in your life."

I nodded and I knew she was right.

I finished my food and then we all went outside and sat on the patio. The night was warm and the stars were out in the sky. I felt like I was in a different world.

"So what do you think?" Dennis asked.

"I think it's amazing," I said.

"So what do you want to do now?" Chastity asked.

"I don't know," I said. "I don't know if I want to do anything right now."

"Why not?" Dennis asked.

"I don't know. I guess I just want to enjoy this moment for a while."

"I understand," Chastity said. "I think you should just take it easy and enjoy life."

"You're right," I said. "I just want to take it all in."

I was feeling so happy and content that I didn't even mind the fact that I was still hungry.

Dennis and Chastity asked me a lot of questions about the restaurant and the town. I answered them as best I could and they seemed to enjoy the conversation

He was a natural when it came to communicating in front of people.

Nick was the opposite. He preferred to be alone, to be in his own thoughts, and to mull over a problem. He had always been an introvert, and he had found it difficult to make small talk with strangers. He was very private, and he hated being the center of attention. He'd always felt like he was on stage and had to perform for everyone.

Kyle's nerves were already shot from the drive. He knew he had to get used to being in front of people, but he couldn't help but feel a little overwhelmed. He was looking forward to meeting some of the other students, but he was also apprehensive.

He felt a tap on his shoulder and turned to see Nick.

"You okay?"

Kyle nodded. "Yeah. I'm fine."

"Good. I'm going to go get us some food. We can talk more when we're finished."

Nick headed for the cafeteria. Kyle followed, still feeling a little apprehensive. He wasn't sure why he was so nervous. It wasn't like he was about to give a speech. He just needed to get used to being in front of people.

He made it to the cafeteria without any major mishaps. He was pleased to see that the food looked good, and he decided to take a seat at a table in the corner. He watched as other students wandered in and out of the cafeteria. He could see the nervous glances that were exchanged, the subtle shifts of bodies and the way people kept their distance from each other. He felt like he was at a party, but he was the only one who was uncomfortable.

Nick finally returned with a tray full of food. He set it down in the middle of the table and sat down.

"What do you want?"

"I'm going to have the chicken salad sandwich, and you can have whatever you want."

"Chicken salad sounds good. Thanks."

Kyle smiled and started to eat. He took a bite, then another, then another. He ate slowly and enjoyed the taste of the food. It was the first time he had really tasted food in a while, and he was surprised at how good it was.

Nick watched him eat, and he smiled. "I think you're going to be okay."

Kyle nodded. "I'm just a little nervous. I'm used to being alone, and it's a big change to be in a group like this."

"Don't worry. You'll get used to it. I think you'll surprise yourself."

Kyle finished his sandwich and then looked up at Nick. "Do you have any advice for me?"

Nick nodded. "Yes. I think the best advice I can give you is to just be yourself. Don't worry about making mistakes. Just be yourself and people will accept you."

"I think you're right. Thanks."

Nick nodded and then stood up. "I'm going to go get some more food. You want anything else?"

"No. I'm good."

### **_The Rules of Self-Care_**

Self-care is an important part of being a well-adjusted human. In this chapter, we'll look at the rules of self-care: what they are and how to follow them.

#### **1. Be Mindful of Your Needs**

The first rule of self-care is to be mindful of your needs. Your needs are the things you need to take care of yourself. They may include eating a healthy, nutritious diet, getting enough sleep, taking time for relaxation, and managing stress.

#### **2. Make Self-Care a Priority**

It's important to make self-care a priority. You can't be your best self if you don't take care of yourself.

#### **3. Make Time for Yourself**

Make time for yourself. This can be as simple as a few minutes of meditation or reading a book, or it can be more elaborate, like going for a run, taking a hot bath, or cooking a special meal for yourself.

#### **4. Get the Right Kind of Rest**

Make sure you get the right kind of rest. This means getting enough sleep, which is important for your physical and mental health. It also means avoiding too much screen time, which can be draining.

#### **5. Take Care of Your Body**

Take care of your body. This includes eating healthy foods, exercising regularly, and getting plenty of sunlight.

#### **6. Take Care of Your Mind**

Take care of your mind. This includes doing things that relax and distract you, such as listening to music, playing board games, or reading a book.

#### **7. Get Involved**

Get involved. This can be as simple as volunteering or joining a club, or as elaborate as becoming a mentor or taking a leadership role in your community.

#### **8. Take Care of Your Spirit**

Take care of your spirit. This includes things like meditating, going on a nature walk, or just taking a few minutes to reflect.

#### **9. Make Self-Care a Habit**

Make self-care a habit. This can include things like setting aside time for self-care every day, such as a few minutes of meditation or a few minutes of journaling.

#### **10. Be Kind to Yourself**

Be kind to yourself. This means treating yourself with love and respect, even when things are difficult.

#### **11. Connect with Others**

Connect with others. This can be as simple as having a few friends over for a cup of tea or as elaborate as volunteering or joining a club.

#### **12. Take Time for Yourself**

Take time for yourself. This can be as simple as having a few minutes of quiet time or as elaborate as going on a vacation.

#### **13. Have Fun**

Have fun. This can include things like playing a game, going out for a walk, or just taking a few minutes to do something you enjoy.

#### **14. Take Care of Your Body**

Take care of your body. This can include things like eating a healthy, nutritious diet, exercising regularly, and getting plenty of sunlight.

#### **15. Take Care of Your Mind**

#### **16. Get Involved**

#### **17. Take Care of Your Spirit**
